                {
                  "key": "response",
                  "value": {
                    "stringValue": "Here's a self-contained prompt you can paste (into this session or a fresh one):\n\n```\nIn C:\\proj\\Oltp-Extracter, extend extractor/writer.py so that every time a JSON\nrecord file is actually written to disk, a matching row is also appended to a\nCSV file — creating the CSV with a header row if it doesn't exist yet, or\nappending to it if it does.\n\nRequirements:\n- CSV path: extracted\\records.csv (single file at the root of the output\n  directory, alongside the per-session subfolders) — add a --csv-path CLI\n  flag to extractor/cli.py to override the default, defaulting to\n  <output>\\records.csv.\n- Columns: the same 12 output fields in the same order as the JSON schema\n  (Session ID, Session Date, Model, Agent, Skills, Cost USD, Input Tokens,\n  Output Tokens, Cache Read Tokens, Cache Creation Tokens, JIRA Key, User\n  Email), plus a Request ID column (from _meta.request_id) for traceability\n  back to the JSON file.\n- Idempotency: only append a CSV row when write_record() actually writes a\n  new JSON file (i.e. when it doesn't return None for an already-written\n  request_id) — so running the CLI twice must not duplicate rows, matching\n  the existing JSON idempotency guarantee. Don't add separate duplicate\n  detection for the CSV; just gate the append on the same check.\n- Use Python's built-in csv module (csv.DictWriter), write the header only\n  when creating the file for the first time, and open in append mode\n  otherwise. Handle concurrent-safety the same way state_store.py does\n  (this doesn't need to be as strict as JSON atomic writes, but don't\n  corrupt the file if interrupted mid-write — flush/close properly).\n- Update tests/test_correlate.py or add tests/test_writer.py covering:\n  CSV created with header on first write, rows appended on subsequent\n  distinct records, no duplicate row added when write_record() is called\n  again for an already-written request_id.\n- After implementing, run the existing test suite (python -m pytest tests/ -v),\n  then do a full run against the real data (python -m extractor --input\n  received --output extracted) and confirm extracted\\records.csv has exactly\n  one row per JSON file under extracted\\, then run the CLI a second time and\n  confirm the CSV row count is unchanged (idempotency).\n\nDon't touch otlp_flatten.py, jira.py, agent.py, correlate.py, or state_store.py\n— this is additive to writer.py/cli.py only.\n```"
